(1178, 1, '2020-03-18 15:53:03', '2020-03-18 15:53:03', '[vc_row][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][ultimate_heading main_heading=\"Classic Guitar\" alignment=\"left\" margin_design_tab_text=\"\"]\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The <b>classical guitar</b> (also known as the <b>classic guitar</b>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_guitar#cite_note-1\">[1]</a></sup> <b>nylon-string guitar</b> or <b>Spanish guitar</b>) is a member of the <a title=\"Guitar\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guitar\">guitar</a> family used in <a title=\"Classical music\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_music\">classical music</a>. An acoustic wooden <a title=\"String (music)\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/String_(music)\">string</a> instrument with strings made of <a title=\"Catgut\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catgut\">gut</a> or <a title=\"Nylon\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nylon\">nylon</a>, it is a precursor of the modern <a title=\"Acoustic guitar\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acoustic_guitar\">acoustic</a> and <a class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Electric guitars\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_guitars\">electric guitars</a>, both of which use metal <a title=\"String (music)\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/String_(music)\">strings</a>. Classical guitars are derived from the Spanish <a title=\"Vihuela\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vihuela\">vihuela</a> and <a title=\"Gittern\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gittern\">gittern</a> in the fifteenth and sixteenth century, which later evolved into the seventeenth and eighteenth century <a title=\"Baroque guitar\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baroque_guitar\">Baroque guitar</a> and later the modern classical guitar in the mid nineteenth century.</p>\r\n[/ultimate_heading][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_single_image image=\"1155\" img_size=\"1000x1000\"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][v